SIMPLE: tiptoe
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tiptoe
<hw>Tip"toe`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Tiptoes</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <def>The end, or tip, of the
toe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He must . . . stand on his <qex>typtoon</qex> [tiptoes].</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Upon his <qex>tiptoes</qex> stalketh stately by.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To be a tiptoe</b></col>, <col><b>To stand a
tiptoe</b></col>, <col><b>To stand on tiptoe</b></col> <it>or</it>
<col><b>To be on tiptoe</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to be awake or alive to
anything; to be roused; to be eager or alert; <as>as, <ex>to be a
tiptoe</ex> with expectation</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1512 -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tiptoe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tiptoe
<hw>Tip"toe`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Being on
tiptoe, or as on tiptoe; hence, raised as high as possible; lifted up;
exalted; also, alert.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Night's candles are burnt out, and jocund day⟦br⟧
Stands <qex>tiptoe</qex> on the misty mountain tops.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Above the <qex>tiptoe</qex> pinnacle of glory.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Noiseless; stealthy.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With
<xex>tiptoe</xex> step.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tiptoe mirth</b></col>, <cd>the highest degree of
mirth.</cd> <rj><au>Sir W. Scott.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tiptoe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tiptoe
<hw>Tip"toe`</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To step or walk on
tiptoe.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tiptop</ent>⟦br⟧
